lines.name: Andromeda
lines.description: "Fantastic climbing with a sting in the tail."
lines.location: The massive flake which hangs to the right on the main face where the trail meets the cliff at the top of the talus slope.

lines.name: Backwoods Brawlin
lines.description: Strenuous Off Width
lines.location: Starts as Crenellation but steps left

lines.name: Crenellation
lines.description: Located 25m along the treed ledge

lines.name: First Fistfight On Mars
lines.description: Starts below the main arete and climbs up and right into a small dihedral, through the crux and onto the cleaner red rock face of the Fortress’ more prominent lookout.
lines.location: Located 5m right of where trail reaches the cliff

lines.name: Made in the Shade
lines.description: Look for band of black rock
lines.location: Located at top and left of talus slope

lines.name: Princess Don’t Need Rescuing
lines.description: Located 6m past the slight corner start of Crenellation  and Backwoods Brawlin

lines.name: Algoma Gold
lines.description: Head up the arete right of Dr. Stoppage. A few sidepulls to a step out right. Slopey holds and an awkward crux with a blocky undercling. Cool arete moves to the top of the pillar.
lines.location: Obvious bolted arete right side of crag.

lines.name: Approach Shoe Express
lines.description: Pitch 1, Climb slab to anchors on right.Pitch 2, Move right, climb layback corner to a ledge. Follow steep arete until you can move left onto the face.Pitch 3, 3rd class scramble to bolted anchors
lines.location: 2nd route from the left on Ramparts cliff

lines.name: Doctor Stoppage
lines.description: Up the wide crack with a small roof. Big holds and fun climbing!
lines.location: Look for the only wide crack left of a pinnacle.

lines.name: Marshmallow Man
lines.description: Pitch 1, Up slight broken groove to belay next to a pine tree.Pitch 2, up, step right to small arete, climb that. Continue to anchors at top.
lines.location: 30 m left of Doctor Stoppage (Big black crack on right end of cliff)
lines.protection: Anchors at top of cliff. No rings. (Walk off)

lines.name: Bullets before Breakfast
lines.description: Pitch 1, Climb the rib to a ledge with juniper.Pitch 2, Cross a gully on the right, traverse a ledge until a couple of steep moves lead to the belay.Pitch 3, Climb the wall above the Lucky LedgePitch 4, Steep groove blocked by a chockstone, and a slab lead to bolts just below topPitch 5, Scramble couple meters to huge North Channel Ledge, and follow flagging tape 70m to left to a bolt belay at end of ledge.Pitch 6, Exposed climbing up a wall to a ledge with two prominent trees that have been hit by lightning.Pitch 7, Easy climb to very top of cliff.
lines.location: Left side of Riverside Rock, where prominent vertical wall rises 75 m at its highest point to a large forested ledge (The North Channel)
lines.protection: Bring 12 draws and a 70 metre rope if you want to descend by rappel. Alternatively, hike down.

lines.name: Full Moon
lines.description: Pitch 1, start up a short wall with 3 bolts leading to an optional anchor just below the big ledge.At the roof near the end of the pitch, step left and down to belay.Pitch 2, Follow bolts up and left over roofs through a scoop to a mantle. Traverse left several meters to anchor.Pitch 3, Follow bolts to a rightward traverse, then over the roof. This pitch puts you on The BalconyPitch 4, Starts several meters to the left in a groove with a large pine tree at your back. Followw bolts up and left; avoid using the old tree. This pitch puts you on The Porch. Continue 2-3 m up and right to anchor bolts left of a large flakePitch 5, Traverse right and climb onto the flake. Follow bolts out right to a left facing layback flake. Head up back left of the arete finishing to the right around the final small roof. This puts you on The AtticPitch 6, Exit pitch leading to the top of the cliff. Anchor bolts are located climbers left on a small rock face 20 cm above the ground
lines.location: Start is approx. 25 m right of The Stars at Night on a short face below a large ledge. The right side of this feature is a major right facing corner made of black rock with a wide crack.

lines.name: Long May You Run
lines.description: Pitch one: Short gully to a small crux (5.10a)Pitch two: Good incuts to a steep face (5.10b)Pitch three: Wandering features to a small roof (5.10b)Pitch four: Good crimps left into awkward wall (5.10d)Pitch five: Fun and featured, left around roof with tricky jam (5.10+ or 11a, jury is still out)Pitch six: Short but tricky corner to the top (5.9)Descent: Walk off trail to the right
lines.location: Up the tallest most continuous part of the wall on the right side of the main cliff.

lines.name: The Stars at Night
lines.description: Pitch 1, Stick clip the first bolt. Follow bolts past a couple of roofs and grooves and exit right to a stance at base of chimney-like feature on right.Pitch 2, From anchor, follow bolts left and climb groove on left side of arete, then cross over the arete back right into the top of a chimney. Head up corner to a large ledge.Pitch 3, Climb up groove on right to a slab, past a flake system, up to a bolt, past a grassy ledge with rings. Faceclimb to a right traverse. Follow layback system to anchors on left.Pitch 4, Follow flake system until blocked by a roof, move right around the roof. Climb up steep overhanging face exiting through a right-facing dihedral onto a long narrow ledge. Traverse left across the Balcony to a much wider platform called the Terrace.Pitch 5, Climb up and right to the next small edge.Pitch 6, Follow bolts up corners and slabs to a top-out on a ledge system with rappel rings.
lines.location: Left most route on Lookout Wall

lines.name: Cadence
lines.description: A fantastic and visually-pleasing arête with a spicy transition to the top.

lines.name: Exhilaration
lines.description: Line to the right of The Bee Whisperer. Climb the rock face to the system of cracks and flakes and a small roof which needs to be pulled to reach the anchor shuts. A high fun factor climb

lines.name: Future Is Now
lines.description: Easy and fun trad line on the left side of the Balcony. Follow dihedral all the way to the top where you can find anchors. Access to the top of the climb from the Balcony. Short walk up the gully on the right of The tooth to get there.

lines.name: Pol-Italia
lines.description: A high-fun-factor climb.

lines.name: Shark Bait
lines.description: A short, but aesthetic line on The Tooth (separate rock to climbers right from Balcony)Layback, kick your feet up and enjoy the tension

lines.name: Tapes & CD's
lines.description: Tread lightly on the hollow flakes to gain the first handful of bolts. A cruxy traverse right, followed by a pumpy finish.

lines.name: Welcome to canada
lines.description: from rockclimbing.com - "Start at the base of an imposing chimney between a skyscaper sized detached tower and the main wall. shimmy up some easy 5th class (5.4?, 60ft, 2 bolts) to the belay/rapstation on top of a huge chock stone in the chimney. Proceed directly up the chimney, past the chockstone to a bolted anchor with chains. (5.7+/5.8, 90ft, 6 bolts) Two raps to the ground with a single 60M, or a single double rope rap on the outside of the spire." from the last belay station you can trad up the last short easy pitch to the top of the spire, but you'll have to down climb back to said belay station.

lines.name: Agent Ornge
lines.description: The first route established on the cliff.  Named for the local climber who spotted the cliff while flying for Ornge.  Climbs the obvious dihedral.  And yes, there’s no ‘a’ in Ornge.

lines.name: Ain’t no Cplus
lines.description: Start up some easy ledges to the first bolt, and make some tricky face moves to the top.

lines.name: Battle of the Bulge
lines.description: Start on the face just right of Agent Ornge and follow the bolt line to the arête.

lines.name: Ceasers on the Patio
lines.description: Harder than it looks.  First climb on the left of the cliff on the smaller wall.  Start in a small corner and climb out through some surprisingly challenging moves.  Don’t expect huge jugs at the top either.
lines.location: Route#1 climbers left of the crag

lines.name: Dirty but Nice with Tequila and Ice
lines.description: Head up to a ledge. Up the dihedral, continuing through to the next two bolts, avoiding the easy ramp. Once at the fourth bolt move to your right to the final bolt.

lines.name: Dodo's Delight
lines.description: Sport climb in the middle

lines.name: The Eviscerator
lines.description: Unknown

lines.name: Exalted Dragon
lines.description: Climb up a sloping dihedral followed by a overhanging dihedral. Get above the ledge and head for the anchors.

lines.name: Game of Thrones
lines.description: Unknown

lines.name: Hurray for the Riff Raff, Kiss
lines.description: Climb up the slab to briefly run alongside Unprotected Footsies, then climb straight up the face. Once you reach the ledge, continue up the arête to the left.
lines.location: A few feet to the right of UF.

lines.name: JJ
lines.description: Dihedral climbing.

lines.name: Lazy Beaver
lines.description: Start on the same boulder start as Little Miss and follow the bolt line right

lines.name: Little Miss
lines.description: Starts with small bouldering project to gain a ledge and follows the dihedral and finishes out through a roof.   Fun climb with a challenging finish.

lines.name: New Kid on the Block
lines.description: Unknown    5.11a (no pillar, 5.10c(with pillar)

lines.name: Project2
lines.description: Unknown

lines.name: Steel Barr
lines.description: Start up fairly easy climbing in big side pulls until things start to get hard.  Then make some powerful and technical moves with atrocious feet through the next few bolts

lines.name: Suck it up Buttercup
lines.description: Start up the dihedral and clip the first bolt. Zig zag a bit left and right, then head up to the top.

lines.name: Unprotected Footsies
lines.description: Starts in the little gully, up to the slab. Moving up and out to the left for a couple of burley moves then transitioning to some easy moves to the end.

lines.name: Wet and Wild American Summer
lines.description: Climb up chossy looking features.  Furthest right route on the small west wall.

lines.name: Nose Job
lines.description: Stiff start with techy route finding. Combo with 5.9 Rhinoplasty on the upper half for an awesome 2-pitch route!Can rap route to the climbers right with a 60 meter rope.
lines.location: At the base of the nose, starts on the right half, to the left of Pinnacle Crack.

lines.name: Rhinoplasty
lines.description: Starts on top of Nose Job. Excellent exposed climbing on the face, then along the arete to the top.
lines.location: Starts on top of Nose Job.

lines.name: Myopic
lines.description: Starts to the right of a large pillar of rock. The first bolt for the first pitch is quite high and requires a scramble up easy climbing.1st pitch - 5.10c2nd pitch - 5.9 (traverse left, run-out first bolt)3rd pitch - 5.8 (straight up)None of the anchors have rings (the route cannot be repelled without adding quick links or bailer carabiners). At the last anchors there is a large pine tree with tat and a quicklink to the climbers left. Requires 2x ropes to pull off first repel. A very easy walk off is on climbers right which takes you to the trail back to the base of the climb.
lines.location: 3rd or fourth route from the right (depends on how much development continues). Route starts to the right of a large rock pillar with a high first bolt.

lines.name: Bird Pot
lines.description: left route of the two routes on the bluff
lines.location: located on the bottom skiers right pitch of the downhill ski run. there is a litte bluff just over the snowmaking pipes
lines.protection: 3 bolts and two hangars for an anchor. easy walkoff . shares an anchor.

lines.name: Party Cannon
lines.description: longest route on the bluff. Follow the blocky terrain and finnish with a fun slab
lines.location: located on the skiers right of the last pitch of the downhill ski run. walk over the snowmaking pipe and walk 5 m into the woods. right most bolt line of 2
lines.protection: 4 bolts, 2 hanger anchor, shares with i don't like moguls

lines.name: Crescent
lines.description: I think it is ok to move traverse right to get around the bulge around bolt 3 or so, maybe I'm off though and you're supposed to try to go direct through that?

lines.name: Easier Than Teenage Naked Girls
lines.description: A nice climb up a discontinuous crack, with a thinker move mid-way up.
lines.location: Just to right of a block.
lines.protection: Single rack from .2 thru 2 (Black Diamond sizes). A small nut is useful too.

lines.name: Pink Rabbit
lines.description: Step across the mini-cavern and establish on this fun face climb.

lines.name: Traverse Climb
lines.description: A true adventure. It is hard to think of a more apt name for this route - other contenders might be "lichen sweeper", "get sketched out", "is it over yet?", "scary fun". Starts on the arete of White Rabbit and goes right through a tricky corner, up into the roof system and keeps traversing the roof, carefully skipping each roof exit until you're doing face climbs and run out of crack.
lines.location: Double rack from .2 to 2 and a #4, some bolts at the beginning and at parts of the route where it intersects other routes. Bring some long slings to keep rope drag low. Save a .3 and .4 for the end.

lines.name: Better than Ezra
lines.description: Nice route left of Lost in Face, bit crimpy and tricky at the top.
lines.location: I think there were no bolt hangers on the route, but there are anchors atop the route that can be used to top-rope it.

lines.name: Black Slabbath
lines.description: The obvious black slab, but start in the crack to the left. Bit sparse for protection going up the slab, but a few horizontal cracks take small cams well. Bolted anchors at top.
lines.location: Green totem, blue totem, orange tote, black totem, .2 (black diamond X4)

lines.name: Breakfast Special
lines.description: "Just good fun"

lines.name: Danger Mouse says "Good Grief!"
lines.description: Slab climb with some fun moves. To start, you need to scramble up to a ledge that feels a little high off the ground to the first bolt

lines.name: Dressing/No Dressing
lines.description: Nice face climb, a bit runout for first bolt or two, so a small cam or two may be desired.

lines.name: Fully Completely
lines.description: Fun route with a couple hand jams at the start, some juggy ledges, and a tricky move off a huge jug on an overhang.      If you have the small Kenora guide book, this is the route on the cover photo.
lines.location: Anchors at the top. This can be setup on top-rope by climbing an easier nearby route.

lines.name: Lost in Face
lines.description: Thin crack, move up through 3 bolts (no more), climbing face to right of the crack. Crux is some tricky moves right above the 3rd bolt, then up to a tiny roof, then move up left and go to the chains.
lines.location: 3 bolts at the start, chains at the top. Cams recommended (Black Diamond sizing): .3, .5, .75, 1

lines.name: Matt Dennison Memorial
lines.description: Keep on the arete the whole way up, fun slopey bulge to surmount at the end.

lines.name: Notably Gnarly
lines.description: Shares the start with Tito Puentes Latin Mambo, moves up and left after the obvious feature...probably that is the crux.
lines.location: pretty far left on the cliff

lines.name: Sendsation
lines.description: Nice crimpfest that feels overhung, but that's just your arms talking.

lines.name: Stumped
lines.description: A fun route, with sloping ledges and some super balancy moves.
lines.location: Starts near a tree near an undercut far to the left of a huge corner crack.

lines.name: Superfly
lines.description: Start on face to right, stemming over to face on left to get the first bolt or two. Then stay on it and up the arete. Crux can be done sticking to the arete....I unfortunately was too tempted and stemmed to left wall to get through it.

lines.name: Tito Puentes Latin Mambo
lines.description: This shares the same start with Notably Gnarly, but goes to the right after the feature (and is much easier than Notably Gnarly in my opinion).

lines.name: Anyone's Guess?
lines.description: Starts right and underneath of obvious roof. Follow crack to roof and pull through for an obvious mossy finish.
lines.location: No protection, just the water below. Careful at higher heights. Be sure to push off if necessary. Keep your chin up and legs closed!

lines.name: Keep Your Legs Closed
lines.description: Starts up obvious crack to a mossy ledge midway up. Stable to the finish. Easy down climb to the right of the cliff.

lines.name: Not a clue
lines.description: Hang left of the roof. Enjoy some 'stemy' bits with some lay back crack manoeuvres.

lines.name: Which One?
lines.description: Mostly jugs and solid feet to the first ledge. Scrabble to finish.

lines.name: Crack of Dawn
lines.description: Crux is at the start, takes gear well, wanders a bit so bring a couple slings.
lines.location: Crack to the right of Ticked Off.
lines.protection: A #4 or #5 C4 fits well in the wide crack above the start, after that a single rack of cams and a few long slings. Anchors at top.

lines.name: Drugs
lines.description: You may want to stick clip this one, the first bolt is about 4 meters up. Fun moves on sometimes sharp holds.
lines.location: The start is to the left of a pine tree that will grope you if you try to walk between it and the cliff.

lines.name: The Shadow
lines.description: Crux is higher up, where there are two cracks, one to the left and one to the right. Footholds disappear. I think I had to tend left a bit to get through it.

lines.name: Ticked Off
lines.description: The crux for this route is making the 2 or three moves off the ground to get above the bulging start.
lines.location: This is the leftmost route when facing the cliff on the shore that starts from the shore (some further routes start mid-way up the cliff, you have to hike a different trail to get to them).

lines.name: Beer Goggles
lines.description: You'll be ready to move that refrigerator after this compression route - hope your slab game is on point for the top.

lines.name: Chick Tooth
lines.description: One route to the right of the left arete. A hard slab, right off the water, super fun.

lines.name: Corkscrew
lines.description: Wonderful chimney, bruise your knees and get some great practice for Steck Salathe. Goes up the chimney, and then up the slab. Have your belayer anchor to the ground bolt so they don't crack their skull on the roof if the leader takes a whip.

lines.name: On a Wing and a Prayer
lines.description: Tough little cookie with some strenuous liebacks.

lines.name: WaaWaate
lines.description: Cool line that goes up right diagonally, over a rocking rock, and to the top. You can can use a separate rap anchor at the top to get back to the base of the route.

lines.name: Dolomedes
lines.description: Right climb on the wall. Follow small crimps and chips before meeting up with Sempervirens to top out.
lines.location: Sling the spruce or white pines at the top for an anchor. Long slings recommended.

lines.name: Sempervirens
lines.description: Start on the left side of the wall. Thin feet to start with small cracks and blocks on the left side. Once you are halfway up, the climb eases into easy slab climbing to the top. Boat belay recommended.
lines.location: Sling the spruce or white pines at the top for an anchor. Long slings recommended.

lines.name: Alien Life Form
lines.description: This is the direct most route up the face. Good ledges moves into a blank face with decent feet and small crimps to get you to the top
lines.location: Obvious long face on the wall.
lines.protection: Approach from the right and drop a rope from the trees at the top

lines.name: Cat Sandwich
lines.description: Easy, fun climbing. Shares the start with Alien Life Form, and deviates to the right near the top. Boat belay needed.

lines.name: We're Going to Need a Bigger Net
lines.description: If you have ever been out fishing in Mills Lacs you will know this is an extremely remote link of lakes. This large granite face rises directly out of the water. At about 50', this free climb can be intimidating, with a drop into water that is anywhere from 10-15 feet deep at the base. This climb is about a 30 minutes boat ride from Pine Point Resort and is very secluded
lines.location: Boat. The only way this climb is accessible is by a 30 minute boat ride from the Pine Point Resort. I would reccommend showing this map to the resort owner of either PPR or Thunderbird Resort on the lake.
lines.protection: Deep water if you feel confident enough   Otherwise you can approach from the right and drop a top rope

lines.name: Crackle. Splitter. Pop.
lines.description: The crux moves are getting off the ground. It is a thin, crimpy, layback crack with chip feet until you reach the pocket half way up the wall.
lines.location: Right obvious crack in the middle of the wall
lines.protection: Approach from the right and rig a top rope above the crack

lines.name: Fruity Stripes
lines.description: Easiest route on the wall. Follow the obvious crack up and either finish to the climbers left or continue up straight to the top.
lines.location: Several large pine trees make for solid anchors

lines.name: Wisdom's Teeth
lines.description: Crux at the top. Loose rocks but good solid holds. One of many possibilities in the Area
lines.location: Right side of the slickest face. Scramble the boulders at the bottom to get to the face. To get down, walk to the right and scramble down or setup a rap.
lines.protection: No bolts, pinscars and cracks for pro. Trees for anchoring at the top.

lines.name: Jaws
lines.description: No text - use the 'Improve This Page' link to add something useful!

lines.name: Bad Beta
lines.description: Start up into the corner and try an reach the big triangular jug, then climb up the corner to the top.

lines.name: Bethel 1
lines.description: Venture up to the slabby ledge and traverse over to the right, pull the move out to the face, continue to the top. There is a hanging belay bolt for this climb.
lines.location: All the way out left over water.

lines.name: Bethel 9
lines.description: Crack climb with good protection.

lines.name: Centre Line
lines.description: Newer line to the right of the shire.

lines.name: The Hardest Warmup
lines.description: Harder than it looks.

lines.name: Highball Low Number
lines.description: Short and bouldery.
lines.location: Furthest right of the main series of routes. #9 on topo

lines.name: If it ain't got that Swing
lines.description: Head straight up until the second bolt, where you traverse right over to the third bolt. Try not to swing off on the way.
lines.location: On right side of the first block as you encounter Bethel.

lines.name: Layback Attack
lines.description: Climb up to the roof and as indicated by the title, attack the layback to pull up to the final move.
lines.location: On left side of the first block as you encounter Bethel.

lines.name: Ledge Hopper
lines.description: Big moves between ledges, gets a little more crimpy towards the top.

lines.name: The Shire
lines.description: Head left as you get to a small roof. Then go straight up, staying well right of an arete.

lines.name: Starfish
lines.description: Hanging belay bolt that gets you going onto a slightly overhanging face. Pull up to a ledge and then easier climbing from there.
lines.location: First over-water route from the land.

lines.name: Water World
lines.description: Hanging belay bolt at the bottom. Climb up to the overhanging chunk of rock, pull some difficult moves up to a good ledge and continue up.
lines.location: Second line of bolts out over the water.

lines.name: Frictionless
lines.description: Watch your back if you fall, consider stick-clipping. Once you access the ledge with your feet, transition left to the slab.
lines.location: The bottom right of a boulder.

lines.name: Harvey's #2
lines.description: head up to the bolts left of the graffiti.
lines.location: First bolted line on the left, starting at the base of the right leaning arc,

lines.name: Harvey's #4
lines.description: Open project, crimpy

lines.name: Harvey's #5
lines.description: Top rope climbing on hard slab.

lines.name: Mama Bear
lines.description: Start off of an obvious shelf.

lines.name: Hwy 69
lines.description: Visible from the road

lines.name: Caddel Road Icefall
lines.description: On private property, be nice.

lines.name: Dr. Tongue's Cherry Elixir
lines.description: Grab some crappy holds and throw your left foot out to a slippery foot hold and start working your way up using an awkward pinch. An excellent, sustained climb.

lines.name: Isengard
lines.description: Start up the crack on the left, eventually switching into another crack further left halfway up, reach the ledge 20m up and follow another crack up the last 5m to the bolts at the top. Good protection for leading.

lines.name: Sam and Frodo Go for a Hike
lines.description: Awkwardly climb up to the ledge and complete the crux right at the start of the climb, follow the crack to the top.

lines.name: Sam and Frodo Go for a Walk
lines.description: Either start up the easy climbing of the crack on the left, or start on the harder crack on the right and work your way up and left to join the main crack. This makes it closer to 5.9.

lines.name: Bad Water
lines.description: Scramble up a sketchy ledge to the belay, stick clip the first low bolt, stay on the arête up into a couple hard roof moves out of the crux to the top anchors. Stay out of the dihedral to avoid water and rope catching rock on the arête.
lines.location: To the right of the tower at the western edge of the climbable rock at the crag.

lines.name: Born From
lines.description: Out of the boat climbing, if you don’t want to traverse, straight up to a ledge into an small run out on a fun layback on a double flake. Note: this route has some loose rock, seconding from top anchors is recommended rather than top-roping other climbers.

lines.name: Caulk and Blood
lines.description: Follow the arête to a tricky small roof, moves into a challenging crux out of the roof, then easy climbing to the top.

lines.name: Lake Effect
lines.description: Easy start into serious 5.10 climbing, follow the seam past the first crux and move right into a fun finger crack second crux.

lines.name: One in the Stink
lines.description: Scramble up rock on left, hard mono pocket crux at first bolt to easy climbing and small run out after the last bolt.

lines.name: Riverlands
lines.description: Follow the slab to the right of Lake Effect up the arête, crossing over to the bulging overhanging crack, throw some fun moves with satisfying footwork, easy moves to the top or jam your way up the crack to make things interesting.

lines.name: Tower That Was
lines.description: On the rock pile right of Born From, start up some textbook finger jams straight up, 4th clip lengthened due to hollow rock.

lines.name: Chickadee
lines.description: Climb the face at the steep small ramp to the ledge, followed by a small cruxy face to easier terrain above.

lines.name: Parallel Pleasure
lines.description: Stay in between the parallel seams in the rock, following the bolts.

lines.name: Timberwolf 1
lines.description: Easy sport climbing, shorter than most.
lines.location: First climb located to the left of the corner as you approach the crag.

lines.name: Timberwolf 12
lines.description: Follow the bolts to the mini roof exit move.
lines.location: Starts a foot to the right of the trad climb accessing the same shelf.

lines.name: Timberwolf 2
lines.description: Follow the big holds and ledges to the top.
lines.location: The first large corner of the cliff

lines.name: Timberwolf 3
lines.description: Tricky face climbing. Venturing left or right at the bottom may reduce the grade. Fun crimpers at the top with small feet.

lines.name: Timberwolf 4
lines.description: The assigned grade is for sticking to the face. To reduce the grade, you can come around the corner with your right hand.

lines.name: Timberwolf 5
lines.description: Start on the ground to the left of the shelf and then follow the bolt line, great beginner lead.

lines.name: Timberwolf 6
lines.description: Gain the shelf then follow the bolts to the top.

lines.name: Timberwolf 7
lines.description: Great first trad lead. Hit up a couple of shelves to the left-facing flake which brings you to a crack. Follow the crack to the top, passing an old pin and piton. The rappel station is located here.

lines.name: Timberwolf 8
lines.description: Easily gain access to a ledge then try to get on top of an intimidating roof.

lines.name: Spider Peace (DWS)
lines.description: Unleash your inner spider and taste the sweet taste of webs as you climb up the bigger crack.   Can traverse left at the start of the big crack for 10 feet, then go up another crack (V3/4)  Some loose rock.   Lots of different lines all around.
lines.location: Two cracks at the bottom lead to a large crack at the top half.

lines.name: The Canine
lines.description: Go up easy ledges on the southwest corner of the tower to reach a fist crack (good holds on either side) and pull a couple slightly steeper moves to gain a series of ledges. About halfway up, transition to the south face and climb hand sized cracks between blocks to the top. A block slung with lots of webbing and several quicklinks is your anchor.

lines.name: Canyonlands
lines.description: It follows fun edges and moves on solid rock to a big ledge.
lines.location: Directly across from Dorion Tower below the approach trail. Climbs up below the lookout where climbers take photos of people on Dorion Tower.

lines.name: Hazy Waves
lines.description: Climbs the arete right of Green Lantern. Good edges to a bouldery crux into a jug and up easier climbing to a final mantel. Fun!

lines.name: Myopic Adventure
lines.description: Three pitches of super fun crack climbing and jamming on great quality rock! Pitch 1 (5.9 17m) A perfect splitter crack with a rounded mouth. Comfortable and enjoyable jamming and straightforward crack climbing to the top. Bring at least a couple blue and a couple gold C4's or equivalent. Mostly bigger cams to protect. There's some decent feet outside the crack as well to find a comfy position to place pro. Bolted anchor on the ledge above.Pitch 2 (5.6 18m) More of scrambling climb, with a few variations on how you climb it. Felt a little tougher going to the left, but trending right felt like 5.6. Easy gear placements.Pitch 3 (5.8 25m) A somewhat intimidating right facing roof section with a beautiful series of cracks running up it. There are great locations for gear throughout and tons of options for feet. It gets kind wide near the top, and sometimes there's a loose stone or two. Exit teh widening crack with root running into it and use the bolts on the face to the left for a belay.Descent: Probably easiest to walk back down using the scramble (with a rope to protect it). Walk a dozen or so meters further onto the top and look for the birch tree with a rope around it running down a gully. Scramble down this, then follow the gully down and right to return to the start.
lines.location: For full directions and beta, strongly recommend picking up Aric Fishman's guidebook Thunder Bay Climbing. Climb up the boulder field towards the large amphitheater area. Turn into the bush just up from the boulder field and cross just below the bottom of the cliff. Continue past several beautiful crack lines until you see the right facing splitter corner crack. This is the start of pitch 1.
lines.protection: Lots of  big cams (below #4). A single #4 is handy, though not completely necessary. At least a couple #3's and a couple #2's are basically required.

lines.name: Priority Check
lines.description: Pitch 1 (5.9) An amazing first pitch of varied and enjoyable crack climbing. The resting and gear placement positions are really interesting. Be careful in the first couple meters as there is a slightly loose feeling side pull for your right hand. Just follow the crack straight to the top where you'll find a set of anchors with rap rings.Pitch 2 (5.6) Really dirty, lichen covered and the top out has pretty loose rock. Worth the adventure to say you've topped out, and the section immediately above the belay station was fun, but it's not nearly the classic of pitch 1. Place some pro then commit to moving out right and up above the belay. Continue on the adventure, following the crack. Plug in some gear and walk up the slab to a large ledge. Be very careful from here, the rock quality is very suspect and crumbly. Carefully get up over the next little wall and belay off the bolts to your right, or use the giant tree/limb in front of you. Descent: Walk off the top to the 3rd class scramble protected by a rope, or follow the main hiking trail right and back to the parking area. You could also rappel both pitches in 2 rappels (I don't recommend).
lines.location: Full complete directions and descriptions, pick up Aric Fishman's guidebook Thunder Bay Climbing. Head up the boulder field. Before you get up to the amphitheater, turn left and crash through the bush. Com out at an open trail leading down the hill with loose rocks and soil. The climb is on this wall in front of you, facing South. The climb starts in a small left facing corner, with a beautiful clean crack system running up.
lines.protection: A variety of cams and nuts. I placed my #4 very early on the first pitch and used mostly #2 and below sizes from there. Bolted Anchors at the top of pitches.

lines.name: Car Jack
lines.description: A pretty straightforward wide crack, with enough hands and feet to make everything straightforward. Stay in the wide feature to the top.
lines.location: To the right of the bolted line "Curtain Call, 5.10d". See picture topo. Turn off onto the Terry Fox monument and look for the rock wall immidiately on your right. The route is near the left of this rock wall.
lines.protection: Mix of sizes, potentially up to 4". FFA was done solo, not been led on gear yet. 2 bolt anchor on the face with rap rings.

lines.name: Curtain Call
lines.description: Start climbing to the right of the line of bolts, finding holds and tricky feet to stand on a good rest to the right of the third bolt. Then make the cruxy traverse to the left, unlocking the beta to make your way to easier terrain. Finish by climbing the stepping ledges up and left to the bolted anchor on the top above, with a slightly runout last bolt and anchor in the easier terrain. Do not traverse right to the face anchor for "Car Jack 5.7"
lines.location: Turn into the Terry Fox monument off the highway. The wall is immediately on your right. Park on the gravel pullout and look for the clean rock face on the left side of the wall. Curtain Call is to the right of Lens Flare and left of Car Jack. Look for the leftward slopping flake/ledges partway up the climb.
lines.protection: 5 bolts and 2 bolt anchor on top with rap rings.

lines.name: Fingies
lines.description: A perfect finger crack on a blank wall. Super short and bouldery, could be done with a pad or two, or led on gear. Requires good finger crack technique, or just really pumpy laybacking with smearing feet.
lines.location: Drive in to the Terry Fox monument road. Continue past the blasted road cut and just before the road heads up to the monument and parking area, turn left down the previous access road, dirt and old asphalt. Continue to the end of this road, just before the highway. Walk right along the road clearing for ~100m, and keep an eye out for the finger crack in a left facing corner. There's a few opportunities to scramble up and set top rope.
lines.protection: Really small cams. A couple larger trees up top for anchor.

lines.name: Lens Flare
lines.description: A really enjoyable flaring hand crack. The crack pinches off in the few spots but face holds fill in the blanks and make for really creative and engaging climbing. Takes good gear, though the rest positions to place aren't always easy. Start by stepping up the shale band ledges and use some perfect hand jams to gain the positive hold in the crack above. Keep an eye outside the crack for additional holds as needed, and continue up as the crack flares and pinches off alternatingly. Once you've gained the large ledge, the anchor is up and to your right. The giant wedged block at the top was not able to be moved, but best to still be careful.The top was bolted for top rope dry tooling by Kyle Brooks. It was recently scrubbed clean and is in great shape. This area of wall is used for dry tooling, so do not be surprised to see scratch marks. Beware, there is loose rock above all the climbs other than those currently cleaned. The rock quality at this area is very poor, a lot of cleaning required to make safe in summer.
lines.location: Turn off the highway to the Terry Fox Monument. Pull off the road before the road cut, near the long amphitheatre of crumbling rock on your right. The two climbs cleaned here so far are on the climbers left side of this bluff, just before a vertical section of chossy rock and before it all turns to crumbling shale. Refer to the pictures.The easiest way to scramble up and set for top rope is around the far right side of the bluff, just look for the rampiest section and scramble up that and around.
lines.protection: 2 bolt anchor with rap rings. Gear is C4 #1 and below, and will accept nuts in several spots.

lines.name: Sonny with a Chance
lines.description: A really enjoyable slabby balance game from bottom to top. The holds are still somewhat loose and sandy, should clean up by next rock season.
lines.location: This top rope only route is the set of anchors furthest on the climbers right, at the top of the crag. Access by scrambling around right to the top and look for the anchors, with rap rings, in the open flat section with little vegetation.
lines.protection: 2 bolt anchors with rap rings at the top. Rock quality partway through the route (crumbly) does not allow for safe bolting on the face.

lines.name: Tweetie's Place
lines.description: A pretty dirty and mostly neglected crack. There's a couple burly moves to get into the crack, depending on your height/reach. Takes good gear the whole way, hands to thin hands for jams. Used a couple trees up top to build an anchor and scrambled back around from the monument to get down. Pretty scrappy and short a decently fun crack.
lines.location: Drive in to the Terry Fox monument road. Continue past the blasted road cut and just before the road heads up to the monument and parking area, turn left down the previous access road, dirt and old asphalt. Continue to the end of this road, just before the highway. Tweetie's Place is right on the rock wall to your right when facing the highway.
lines.protection: C4 #0.75 - #2, some material for tree anchors.

lines.name: Underclass
lines.description: A really fun and technical line running up the wall, combining finger locks, side pulls, crimps, awkward flaring jams and a beautiful V3 boulder problem at the top. It's probably going to get a single bolt to protect the face section just before the top out, as the last gear is below your feet and the boulder problem is fairly tricky. This last section is Spicy on lead, currently.Step up onto the shale bands as ledges and make your way up to the first big jug. From there, find one of several ways past the undercling problem before starting up the sustained waving finger crack section to the ledge above. Once you've gained the ledge, find the sequence of face moves to move up and throw for the top.The top was bolted for top rope dry tooling by Kyle Brooks. It was recently scrubbed clean of loose rocks, revealing a high quality route, by Tyler Ripku. This area of wall is used for dry tooling, so do not be surprised to see scratch marks. Beware, there is loose rock above all the climbs other than those currently cleaned. The rock quality at this area is very poor, a lot of cleaning required to make safe in summer.
lines.location: Turn off the highway to the Terry Fox Monument. Pull off the road before the road cut, near the long amphitheatre of crumbling rock on your right. The two climbs cleaned here so far are on the climbers left side of this bluff, just before a vertical section of chossy rock and before it all turns to crumbling shale. Refer to the pictures.The easiest way to scramble up and set for top rope is around the far right side of the bluff, just look for the rampiest section and scramble up that and around.
lines.protection: 3 bolts protect until the very thin crack on the middle third, which takes small nuts or cams (I used black Totems). 1 more bolt on the face protecting the final boulder problem before the topout. 2 bolt top anchor with rap rings

lines.name: 4Runner
lines.description: Kinda fun angling crack line. Not a great crack for jamming, but feet and holds everywhere.
lines.location: Right of the roof of New Hemi Charger you can see a crack angling right halfway up, with a short scrambly start.
lines.protection: medium size cams and some nuts.

lines.name: Camaro
lines.description: A scrambly climb, with holds and feet everywhere. Not great.
lines.location: Just right of Pop Da Hood.

lines.name: Hemi Charger
lines.description: A fun crack line on the left of the Hemi Charger wall. Honestly not sure if this is the Hemi Charger route or another line. The crack is extremely dirty and filled with spiderwebs.
lines.location: The obvious crack far left of New Hemi Charger.
lines.protection: Takes small cams and some nuts. 2 bolt rap anchor at top.

lines.name: New Hemi Charger
lines.description: A fun one move wonder type of climb. Head up to the roof, and tackle getting around the lip.
lines.location: The obvious right side of the large roof, on the left side of the crag.

lines.name: Pop Da Hood
lines.description: Really fun balancy, slabby climb. Keep off the left ledges and stay on the slabby face.
lines.location: Just in front of you as you enter the crag from the access trail.
lines.protection: 3 bolts and bolted anchor. No rap rings, can scramble off to clean.
